{{Politics of North Korea|Related topics}}
The alleged '''illicit activities of the North Korean state''' include [[Illegal drug trade|manufacture and sale of illegal drugs]], the manufacture and sale of counterfeit goods, [[human trafficking]], [[arms trafficking]], [[Wildlife trade|wildlife trafficking]], [[counterfeit money|counterfeiting currency]] (especially the [[United States dollar]] and [[Chinese yuan]]), [[terrorism]], and other areas.<ref name="Nautilus">{{cite web|url=http://nautilus.org/publications/books/dprkbb/terrorism/dprk-briefing-book-curtailing-north-koreas-illicit-activities/|title=DPRK Briefing Book : Curtailing North Korea's Illicit Activities|author=Balbina Hwang|publisher=Heritage Foundation|date=August 25, 2003|accessdate=April 8, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SLgVJkRm|archivedate=4 Sep 2014}}</ref><ref name="NYTpg4">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/23/magazine/23counterfeit.html?pagewanted=4&_r=0|title=No Ordinary Counterfeit|author=Stephen Mihm |publisher=New York Times|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SLgbhjs1|archivedate=4 Sep 2014|deadurl=no|date=July 23, 2006|accessdate=April 9, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/13/north-korean-diplomats-linked-to-lucrative-rhino-horn-trade-in-a/|title=North Korean diplomats linked to lucrative rhino horn trade in Africa|last=Ryall|first=Julian|date=2016-07-13|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2018-03-27|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> It is alleged many of these activities are undertaken at the direction and under the control of, the [[North Korean government]] and the ruling [[Workers' Party of Korea]], with their proceeds going towards advancing the country's [[North Korea and weapons of mass destruction|nuclear and conventional arms production]], funding the lifestyles of the country's elite, and propping up the [[Economy of North Korea|North Korean economy]].<ref name=kan>{{cite book|author1=Kan, Paul |author2=Bechton, Bruce |author3=Collins, Robert |title=Criminal Sovereignty: Understanding North Korea's Illicit International Activities|year=2010|publisher=Strategic Studies Institute |isbn=9781584874324}}{{rp|2}}</ref>

==Overview==
Unlike criminal syndicates, the extensive nature of these illegal endeavors, and the claim that they are directed and sanctioned by the highest levels of government,<ref name=kan />{{rp|1}} has led to the nature of the North Korean state being defined as a form of "criminal sovereignty" by foreign policy experts such as [[Paul Rexton Kan]] and [[Bruce Bechtol]].<ref name=kan />{{rp|3}}

However, there are questions remaining about the level of government involvement in each of the criminal enterprises. Many commentators agree that the North Korean state has been behind counterfeiting currency, human trafficking, the arms trade, etc., but the level to which it has been involved in the drug trade after the collapse of the [[Economy of North Korea#Food distribution system|Public Distribution System]] in the 1990s is not clear as semi-private and private black markets have arisen since then and some high-ranking officials may only be engaged in illicit trade for personal benefit.<ref name=gret>{{cite book|author=Greitens, Sheena|year=2014|title= Illicit: North Korea's Evolving Operations to Earn Hard Currency, Committee for Human Rights in North Korea|isbn=978-0-9856480-2-2|url=http://www.hrnk.org/uploads/pdfs/SCG-FINAL-FINAL.pdf|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SLjbfuGJ|archivedate=4 Sep 2014|deadurl=no }}</ref>{{rp|6}}

===Critical assessment===
The British academic, Hazel Smith, has argued that the allegations have a weak foundation, being largely based on the claims of a few US officials and North Korean defectors. She has pointed out that there have been very few criminal convictions. She has queried the assumption that all the activities are directed by North Korea's government.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/apr/27/north-korea-cliches-debunked-hazel-smith|title=Dangerous, isolated and primed for war? North Korean clichés debunked|first=Hazel|last=Smith|publisher=The Guardian|date=27 April 2015}}</ref>

According to North Korea scholar [[Andrei Lankov]], the country's illicit activities never developed into lucrative hard currency earners. Instead, these activities exposed the country to international condemnation in exchange for marginal gain. Lankov suggests that smuggling was never intended to earn currency for the regime, but was simply a means of survival for diplomats whose funding was cut.<ref name="Lankov2016">{{cite book|last=Lankov|first=Andrei|title=The Real North Korea: Life and Politics in the Failed Stalinist Utopia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FHpYCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA23|year=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-939003-8|page=23}}</ref>

==Drug trade==

It is alleged that North Korea's illegal drug trade dates back to the 1970s and includes the manufacturing, selling, and trafficking of illicit drugs, as well as counterfeit otherwise legal pharmaceuticals.<ref name="Insider">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/north-korea-meth-2014-4|title=North Korea's Huge Role In Global Meth Trade Revealed In Insane Criminal Case|author=Keegan Hamilton|publisher=Business Insider|date=April 4, 2014|accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref> Production began in the mountainous Hamkyung and Yangkang Provinces, particularly in the village of Yonsah, where [[Kim Il-sung]] sanctioned the creation of an [[opium]] farm.<ref name=gret />{{rp|20}}

To provide a cover of legitimacy, the North Korean government uses [[front organization|front companies]], like the Ryugyong Corporation under the control of the [[Workers' Party of Korea|Korean Workers Party]]'s Foreign Relations Department, to conduct clandestine activities.<ref name="NewFocus">{{cite web|url=http://newfocusintl.com/the-dprk-is-capitalist-when-it-wants-to-be-the-story-of-drugs-incorporated-parts-12/|title=The DPRK is capitalist when it wants to be: the story of Drugs Incorporated|author=Staff|publisher=New Focus International|date=August 18, 2012|accessdate=April 26, 2014}}</ref> The company also holds large tracts of land within the country for the sole purpose of growing opium<ref name="Nautilus"/> and each year the company sent tens of thousands of dollars in hard currency to [[Kim Jong-il]] for his use. Unlike most companies, Ryugyong Corporation has no import or export quota restrictions.<ref name="NewFocus"/>

According to defector Yoon Yong Sol, during the [[North Korean famine|famine]] "[t]here were some complaints that during the famine we should be growing grain, not poppies, but the instruction from the central government was that if we grow poppies we can sell the product for 10 times as much to buy grain. ... The only way to earn hard currency is by drugs."<ref name=gret />{{rp|22}}

Reports of [[methamphetamine]] (known as "ice drug" in North Korea) use in the country surfaced in the late 1990s.<ref name="ForeignPolicy">{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2013/11/21/inside_north_koreas_crystal_meth_trade|title=Inside North Korea's Crystal Meth Trade|author=Issac Stone Fish|work=Foreign Policy|date=November 21, 2013|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> According to Isaac Stone Fish writing in ''[[Foreign Policy]]'', the production of methamphetamine in North Korea is done by chemists and other underemployed scientists.<ref name="ForeignPolicy"/> Methamphetamine is given as a medication within North Korea, which has helped to fuel its spread. As the production and sale of opium declined in the mid-2000s, methamphetamine became more pervasive.<ref name="ForeignPolicy"/> To bring in much-needed cash, the international methamphetamine trade began, spreading first to China, and with the drug being made in state-run laboratories.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2013/08/21/how-north-korea-got-itself-hooked-on-meth/|title=How North Korea got itself hooked on meth|author=Max Fisher|work=Washington Post|date=August 21, 2013|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> However, Isaac Stone Fish admitted with regard to his report: "I have no idea what is actually happening inside North Korea".<ref>{{cite news|title=The Black Hole of North Korea|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/09/opinion/09iht-edfish09.html?_r=0|first=Isaac|last=Stone Fish|publisher=''New York Times''|date=8 August 2011}}</ref>

China officially admitted to the drug problem stemming from North Korea in 2004, with [[Jilin Province]] being the most important transhipment point from North Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brookings.edu/research/articles/2010/12/03-china-drug-trafficking-zhang|title=Drug Trafficking from North Korea: Implications for Chinese Policy|author=Yong-an Zhang|publisher=Brookings Institution|date=December 3, 2010|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> The production, storage, financing, and sale of the North Korea's methamphetamine trade reaches multiple countries from the Philippines, the United States, Hong Kong, Thailand, western Africa and others.<ref name="Insider"/> In 2010, five foreign nationals were prosecuted as part of a conspiracy involving North Korea to smuggle 40 pounds of methamphetamine into the United States and to sell it for $30,000 a pound.<ref name="ForeignPolicy"/>

In 2001, income from illegal drugs amounted to between $500 million and $1 billion.<ref name="Nautilus"/> In a 2013 ''[[Washington Post]]'' article, annual revenues from methamphetamine sales are estimated at $100 million to $200 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2013/03/22/report-north-korea-ordered-its-foreign-diplomats-to-become-drug-dealers/|title=Report: North Korea ordered its foreign diplomats to become drug dealers|author=Max Fisher|work=Washington Post|date=March 22, 2013|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref>

Between 1977 and 2003, more than twenty North Korean diplomats, agents, and trade officials have been implicated, detained, or arrested in drug-smuggling operations in more than a dozen countries.<ref name="Nautilus"/> In 2004, two North Korean embassy employees were caught smuggling 150,000 tablets of [[clonazepam]] in Egypt, and in that same year, embassy employees from Bulgaria were arrested in Turkey in possession of over 500,000 tablets of [[Captagon]] (the brand name for the synthetic stimulant fenethylline, or phenethylline), with an estimated street value of $7 million.<ref name=gret />{{rp|37}} The government of North Korea has only admitted that individuals undertook such acts, and not at the direction of the state.<ref name=gret />{{rp|17}}

According to the [[Committee for Human Rights in North Korea]], since 2001 drug trafficking operations by diplomats had ceased, with the focus then becoming the production of drugs to be smuggled by other criminal organizations.<ref name=gret />{{rp|18}}

In 2003, the North Korean owned [[Pong Su]] was intercepted importing heroin into Australia. While four men who had landed pleaded guilty, the ship's four officers were acquitted on all charges.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drug ship officers set free |date=6 March 2006 |publisher=News.com.au |url=http://www.news.com.au/story/0,10117,18360926-421,00.html |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215105940/http://www.news.com.au/story/0,10117,18360926-421,00.html |archivedate=15 December 2007 }}</ref>

==Counterfeiting==

===Currency===
{{See also|Superdollar}}
Counterfeiting currency is alleged to have begun in the 1970s under [[Kim Jong-il]]'s direction; however, the notes produced at the time were not of high quality.<ref name="NYTpg4"/> Since then, and within the jurisdiction of [[Room 39]], the North Korean government has counterfeited $50 and $100 United States banknotes using increasingly sophisticated techniques. In 1994, authorities in Hong Kong and Macao apprehended five North Korean diplomats and trade-mission members carrying around $430,000 in bills that turned out to be "[[superdollar]]" (also called "supernote") counterfeits.<ref name="NYTpg5">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/23/magazine/23counterfeit.html?pagewanted=5&_r=0|title=No Ordinary Counterfeit|author=Stephen Mihm |publisher=New York Times|date=July 23, 2006|accessdate=April 9, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> There have been two primary reasons for counterfeiting: the first is to wage economic warfare against the United States,<ref name="NYTpg4"/> and secondly, to help ease North Korea's domestic economic problems.<ref name="NYTpg5"/> According to a report by Dr. Balbina Hwang of [[American University]], North Korea circulated $100 million in counterfeit currency in 2001.<ref name="Nautilus"/> The revenues from this are estimated at between $15 million and $25 million annually.<ref name="CSM">{{Cite journal|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/2013/1008/New-100-bill-why-North-Korea-won-t-be-very-happy-video|title=New $100 bill: why North Korea won't be very happy|journal=Christian Science Monitor|author=Mike Eckel|date=October 8, 2013|accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref> In 2013, the United States released its newly redesigned [[United States one hundred-dollar bill|100 dollar bill]]. The primary purpose of the redesign was to fight against counterfeiting and prevent the recurrence of the "supernotes" which were produced by North Korea.<ref name="CSM"/>

The [[International Convention for the Suppression of Counterfeiting Currency]] is the primary treaty whereby states agree to criminalize acts of currency counterfeiting. North Korea is not a party to the treaty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://treaties.un.org/pages/LONViewDetails.aspx?src=LON&id=551&chapter=30&lang=en|title=International Convention for the Suppression of Counterfeiting Currency|publisher=United Nations|accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref>

Analyst [[Andrei Lankov]] has described the evidence for the counterfeiting of superdollars as merely circumstantial.<ref name="Lankov2016">{{cite book|last=Lankov|first=Andrei|title=The Real North Korea: Life and Politics in the Failed Stalinist Utopia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FHpYCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA23|year=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-939003-8|page=23}}</ref> Gregory Elich of the Korea Policy Institute has argued that these allegations are unfounded. According to Elich, North Korea's [[Intaglio (printmaking)|intaglio]] press from the 1970s would be incapable of printing the supernotes, and the paper and ink would be extremely difficult for North Korea to produce. Furthermore, he says that the amounts of supernotes produced are too small to be economical.<ref>{{cite web|title=North Korea and the Supernote Enigma|url=http://www.globalresearch.ca/north-korea-and-the-supernote-enigma/8919|first=Gregory|last=Elich|publisher=Global Research|date=7 May 2008}}</ref>

===Counterfeit legal pharmaceuticals===
There have been a few cases of North Korea being implicated in the production of counterfeit [[Viagra]]. These include: a 2004 arrest in [[Seoul, South Korea]] of a man with 4,000 counterfeit Viagra pills; and a 2005 report from Japan that North Korea was producing fake Viagra pills in factories in [[Chongjin]], which were then sold in Hong Kong to customers of other Southeast-Asian countries (including China), and the Middle East.<ref name=gret />{{rp|38}} 

===Counterfeit cigarettes===
Counterfeit cigarettes have been a lucrative item for the country. The trade is believed to have begun in the 1990s and greatly increased in 2002 after Chinese authorities shut down many counterfeit operations in China, which then provided added incentive, knowledge, and capacity which could be relocated to North Korea.<ref name=gret />{{rp|32}} During a 2006 Congressional hearing, Peter A. Prahar of the [[United States Department of State|Department of State]], quoted reports that mentioned the existence of "as many as 12" factories in the DPRK capable of producing "billions of packs of counterfeit cigarettes annually."<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CHRG-109shrg28241/html/CHRG-109shrg28241.htm|title=- NORTH KOREA: ILLICIT ACTIVITY FUNDING THE REGIME|website=www.gpo.gov|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref> The factories appear to be owned and operated by the North Korean military.<ref name=":0" /> The major factories for cigarette production were reportedly based in [[Rajin]], though defectors also mentioned a factory in [[Pyongyang]].<ref name=gret />{{rp|33}}

In 1995, Taiwan stopped a ship and confiscated 20 containers of counterfeit cigarette packaging, which is enough to make 2 million cartons of popular Japanese and British brands.<ref name=gret />{{rp|32}} In 2004, authorities in Vietnam, Taiwan, the Philippines, and Singapore also impounded containers filled with counterfeit cigarettes.<ref name=gret />{{rp|33}} Official congressional testimony in 2006 revealed that North Korea-sourced [[Marlboro (cigarette)|Marlboro brand]] cigarettes had been identified in 1,300 incidents across the United States.<ref name=gret />{{rp|35}} Revenues from counterfeit cigarettes are estimated at between $80 million and $160 million a year.<ref name=gret />{{rp|36}}

==Human trafficking==
{{main|Human trafficking in North Korea}}

North Korea is a "Tier 3" country (those who do not comply with human trafficking laws) as listed by the U.S. Department of State and has retained this ranking since 2007.<ref name="TraffickingReport">{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/documents/organization/226847.pdf|title=Trafficking in Persons Report 2014: KOREA, DEMOCRATIC PEOPLE'S REPUBLIC OF|publisher=U.S. Department of State|year=2014|pages=231–232|accessdate=September 4, 2014}}</ref>
The country is a source country of men, women, and children for sex trafficking and forced labor. Forced labor is used both [[Human rights in North Korea#Internment camps for political prisoners|internally]] and externally. Countries which have North Korean forced laborers include Russia, China, Mongolia, and other places in Central Asia, Europe, Africa, and the Middle East.<ref name="TraffickingReport"/>

While the North Korean government claims these are "contract workers", reports claim that they are actually subjected to forced labor, that their movements and communications are subjected to strict surveillance, and that workers sent overseas do not have a choice in the type of work they will be doing nor do they receive pay for their work.<ref name="TraffickingReport"/>

It is estimated that there are thousands of North Koreans working in logging, construction, and agriculture industries in Russia. These workers reportedly only receive two days of rest each year and face punishment if they fail to meet quotas.<ref name="TraffickingReport"/>

North Korea is not a party to the 2000 UN [[Protocol to Prevent, Suppress and Punish Trafficking in Persons, especially Women and Children|TIP Protocol]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://treaties.un.org/pages/viewdetails.aspx?src=ind&mtdsg_no=xviii-12-a&chapter=18&lang=en|title=Protocol to Prevent, Suppress and Punish Trafficking in Persons, Especially Women and Children|publisher=United Nations|date=April 9, 2014|accessdate=September 4, 2014}}</ref>

==Arms trade==
During the 1980s, North Korea emerged as a ''legal'' arms trader to primarily [[Third World]] countries, exporting relatively inexpensive, technically unsophisticated, but reliable weapons.<ref name="DIAC3">{{cite book|url=https://fas.org/irp/dia/product/knfms/knfms_chp3a.html|title=North Korea: The Foundations for Military Strength |chapter= 3A|publisher=Defense Intelligence Agency|date= 1991|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> During the [[Iran–Iraq War]], some 90% of arms exports from North Korea went to Iran, and between 1981 and 1989, North Korea earned an estimated $4 billion from arms sales.<ref name="DIAC3"/>

North Korea has a known track record in proliferating nuclear and missile technology and in 2001, missile sales came to $560 million.<ref name="Nautilus"/> Following its [[2006 North Korean nuclear test|2006 nuclear test]], international sanctions have sought to limit or prevent North Korea from exporting various types of arms, materials, and technology.<ref name="HuffPost">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/17/north-korea-weapons-trade_n_3610668.html|title=North Korea's Weapons Trade: A Look At A Global Business|author=Foster Klug|work=Huffington Post|date=July 17, 2013|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> Prior to UN sanctions however, countries such as Japan and the United States took unilateral steps to curb such activities.<ref name="Nautilus"/>

UN sanctions now ban all arms, including small arms and light weapons.<ref name="CRS1874"/>{{rp|14}}
North Korea has developed an extensive and complicated arms trade network in an attempt to circumvent sanctions and uses front companies and embassies to traffic weapons.<ref name="Reuters">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/03/11/us-korea-korea-un-idUSBREA2A08020140311|title=Front companies, embassies mask North Korean weapons trade |author=James Pearson|newspaper=Reuters|date=March 11, 2014|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> In a 2014 UN report, [[Syria]], [[Myanmar]], [[Eritrea]], [[Tanzania]], [[Ethiopia]], [[Somalia]] and [[Iran]] were all suspected to have bought weapons from North Korea.<ref name="Reuters"/>

===Incidents===
{{As of|2010}}, trade in banned small arms and ammunition was relatively insignificant, with reports include: imports totaling $45,500 by [[Brazil]] in 2007, of $3.1 million by the [[United Arab Emirates]] in 2006, and $364,400 by Ethiopia in 2005, and $121,400 by [[Mexico]] in 2005.<ref name="CRS1874"/>{{rp|14}}

In 2009, three vessels were intercepted which were carrying North Korean weapons. Western and Israeli intelligence officials believed the weapons were destined for [[Hezbollah]] and [[Hamas]].<ref name="CRS1874"/>{{rp|7}}

In December 2009, Thailand intercepted a charter jet from Pyongyang carrying 35 tons of conventional weapons, including [[surface-to-air missiles]].<ref name="HuffPost"/>

In 2012, the United Nations reported that 445 North Korean-made graphite cylinders (which can be used to produce ballistic missiles) were seized from a Chinese freighter at the South Korean port of [[Busan]] on their way to Syria.<ref name="HuffPost"/>

In 2013, a [[North Korean cargo ship seizure in Panama]] (carrying [[Cuba]]n weapons) took place.

In August 2016, US intelligence tracked a ship sailing under a [[Flag of convenience|convenience flag]] of [[Cambodia]], with a North Korean crew sailing from North Korea to [[Egypt]] was found with carrying 24,000 [[rocket-propelled grenades]] and components for another 6,000. It was ordered and paid by a private Egyptian business, but it is believed that it was for the [[Egyptian Army]]. The value of this order and others is estimated at $23 million.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Warrick|first1=Joby|title=A North Korean ship was seized off Egypt with a huge cache of weapons destined for a surprising buyer|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/a-north-korean-ship-was-seized-off-egypt-with-a-huge-cache-of-weapons-destined-for-a-surprising-buyer/2017/10/01/d9a4e06e-a46d-11e7-b14f-f41773cd5a14_story.html|publisher=''[[The Washington Post]]''|accessdate=25 November 2017|date=1 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/03/04/un-report-new-light-egypts-role-north-korean-weapons-sales/ | title=UN report to shed new light on Egypt's role in North Korean weapons sales| newspaper=The Telegraph| date=2018-03-04| last1=Ryall| first1=Julian}}</ref>

== Wildlife trade ==
Over the past three decades, at least 18 North Korean diplomats have been caught smuggling [[rhino horn]] and [[ivory]], though the real number is considered to be much higher.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://globalinitiative.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/TGIATOC-Diplomats-and-Deceipt-DPRK-Report-1868-web.pdf|title=Diplomats and Deceit: North Korea's Criminal Activities in Africa|last=Rademeyer|first=Julian|date=September 2017|website=Global Initiative Against Transnational Organized Crime|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> North Korean defectors have also reported smuggling of rhino horn and ivory from countries like [[Angola]], [[Ethiopia]], and the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], [[South Africa]] and [[Mozambique]].<ref name=":1" /> Such illegal activity is considered low-risk but highly rewarding for the regime.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/5b1ec8a4-9ee1-11e7-9a86-4d5a475ba4c5|title=North Korea said to be revitalising African wildlife trafficking|last=|first=|date=|website=Financial Times|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>

==Room 39==
{{main|Room 39}}
Room 39 (or Office 39) is the primary government organization that seeks ways to maintain the foreign currency slush fund of North Korea's leader.<ref>{{cite web|title=North Korea's Dollar Store|date=August 5, 2009 |author=David Rose|work=Vanity Fair|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/politics/features/2009/09/office-39-200909|accessdate=September 4, 2014}}</ref> Room 39 oversees many of the government's illegal activities (although the military also has its own illegal activity division) such as counterfeiting and drug production. In 2010, the department was reported to have had 17 overseas branches, 100 trading companies and banks under its control.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk00400&num=6750|title=What Is the No.39 Department?|author=Kim Yong Hun |publisher=DailyNK|date=August 30, 2010|accessdate=September 4, 2014}}</ref> By 2009, the office allegedly had upwards of $5 billion in assets, much of which was spread in banks throughout [[Macau]], [[Hong Kong]], and Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/kim-jong-un-estimated-5-141825342.html|title=Kim Jong-un Estimated To Have Up To $5 Billion In Secret Overseas Accounts|author=Adam Taylor|publisher=Business Insider|date=March 13, 2013|accessdate=September 4, 2014}}</ref>

In August 2014, Yun Tae-hyong, a senior representative of North Korea's ''Korea Daesong Bank'', which is suspected of being under control of Room 39,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/tg962.aspx|title=Treasury Designates Key Nodes of the Illicit Financing Network of North Korea's Office 39|publisher=U.S. Department of the Treasury|date=November 18, 2010|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> was reported to have defected to Russia taking $5 million with him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/north-korean-leaders-money-manager-defects-russia-south-082332404.html|title=North Korean leader's money manager defects in Russia|authors=Ju-min Park and James Pearson|publisher=Reuters|date=August 29, 2014|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref>

In 2015, the European Union placed the [[Korea National Insurance Corporation|Korean National Insurance Company]] (KNIC) under sanctions and added that the KNIC had links to Room 39.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/apr/23/uk-freezes-assets-of-north-korean-company-in-south-london-insurance-nuclear-weapons|title=UK freezes assets of North Korean company based in south London|last=Booth|first=Robert|date=2017-04-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-04-23|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The KNIC (which had offices in Hamburg, Germany and London, United Kingdom) was reported to have had assets of UK£787 million in 2014 and had been involved in scamming insurance markets and making investments in property and foreign exchange.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/kim-cooked-up-nuclear-cash-in-the-suburbs-north-korea-znp25pw5k|title=Kim cooked up ‘nuclear cash’ in the suburbs|last=Gadher|first=Dipesh|date=2017-04-23|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2017-04-23|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|publication-date=|language=en|subscription=Y}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/secrets-of-kims-little-house-in-the-suburbs-ksjz9tv65|title=Secrets of Kim’s little house in the suburbs|last=Gadher|first=Dispesh|date=2017-04-23|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2017-04-23|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en|subscription=Y}}</ref>

==Politically motivated actions==
As well as illegal money-making ventures, North Korea has been condemned for politically motivated criminal acts related to the long-running [[Korean conflict]].

===Terrorism===
In 1988, North Korea was added to the [[State Sponsors of Terrorism]] list for supplying groups with weapons and for their role in the [[Rangoon bombing]] and the bombing of [[Korean Air Flight 858]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfr.org/state-sponsors-of-terrorism/state-sponsors-north-korea/p9364|title=State Sponsors: North Korea|author=Vikaas Sharma|publisher=Council on Foreign Relations|date=June 28, 2008|accessdate=September 4, 2014}}</ref> In 2008 President [[George W. Bush]] agreed to remove North Korea from the list after North Korea met their obligations to provide access to their nuclear program and the resumption of disabling of their nuclear facilities,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7665206.stm | work=BBC News | title=N Korea taken off US terror list | date=October 11, 2008 | accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref> but continued hostilities and the fear that North Korea could sell nuclear weapons to terrorist organizations have called for the nation to be relisted.

In 2017, North Korea was relisted as a terrorist state in response to the murder of [[Kim Jong-nam]], its role in the [[Syrian Civil War]], close relationships with [[Iran]], and it backing Islamic terrorist organizations, especially [[Hamas]].<ref name=NKIL>{{cite web | url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/hamas-thanks-n-korea-for-its-support-against-israeli-occupation/ | title=Hamas thanks N. Korea for its support against 'Israeli occupation'}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/fears-north-korea-crisis-could-10973107 | title=North Korea crisis could increase risk of larger attacks from ISIS| date=2017-08-11}}</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/20/us/politics/north-korea-trump-terror.html Trump Returns North Korea to List of State Sponsors of Terrorism (The New York Times)]</ref>

===International abductions===
Between 1977 and 1983, [[North Korean abductions of Japanese citizens|North Korea abducted several Japanese citizens]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nettv.gov-online.go.jp/eng/prg/prg1786.html|title=Abduction – An Unforgivable Crime|publisher=Japanese Government Internet TV|date=January 23, 2009|accessdate=September 4, 2014}}</ref> North Korea has admitted to abducting 13 Japanese citizens,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mdn.mainichi-msn.co.jp/international/asia/news/20060413p2g00m0in046000c.html|accessdate=2006-05-01|title=North Korea rejects DNA link to Megumi Yokota abduction case|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> and Japan lists 17 as having been abducted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rachi.go.jp/en/ratimondai/jian.html|title=Individual Cases – 17 Abductees Identified by the Government of Japan|publisher=Japanese Government Headquarters for the Abduction Issue|date=May 2011|accessdate=September 4, 2014}}</ref> There are also testimonies which list nine Europeans as being abducted by North Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/international/2008/04/21/01003-20080421ARTFIG00614-les-captives-etrangeresde-la-coree-du-nord.php|title=Les captives étrangèresde la Corée du Nord|date=21 April 2008|publisher=|via=Le Figaro}}</ref>

The purposes of abduction ranges from using the abductees as translators/teachers,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/korea/article/0,2763,812524,00.html|title=
North Korea's kidnap victims return home after 25 years|last=McCurry|first=Justin|accessdate=2006-05-01 | date=October 16, 2002 | location=London | work=The Guardian}}</ref> to become wives,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/id/2087627/|title=Why North Koreans Were Kidnappers|author=Brendan Koerner|publisher=Slate.com|date=August 27, 2003|accessdate=September 4, 2014}}</ref> and to obtain identities for other clandestine operations. During the [[Korean War]] North Korea abducted an estimated 82,959 South Koreans, and in the post-war period South Korea claims that a further 489 [[North Korean abductions of South Koreans|South Koreans have been abducted by North Korea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sukuukai.jp/narkn/|title=North Korean Abduction Victims Worldwide|publisher=National Association for the Rescue of Japanese Kidnapped by North Korea|date=December 2006|accessdate=September 4, 2014}}</ref>

===Hacking===
According to cybersecurity experts, North Korea maintains an army of hackers trained to disrupt enemy computer networks and steal both money and sensitive data. In the previous decade, it was blamed for numerous [[cyber-attack]]s and other hacking attacks in South Korea and elsewhere.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/10/world/asia/north-korea-hack-war-plans.html|title=North Korean Hackers Stole U.S.-South Korean Military Plans, Lawmaker Says|first=Choe|last=Sang-hun|publisher=New York Times|date=10 October 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012061027/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/10/world/asia/north-korea-hack-war-plans.html|archivedate=12 October 2017|df=}}</ref>

After the [[Sony Pictures hack]] in 2014, U.S. government officials stated that the North Korean government was "centrally involved" in the hacking.<ref name=nyt-linkedtokorea>{{cite news|title=U.S. Links North Korea to Sony Hacking|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/world/asia/us-links-north-korea-to-sony-hacking.html?_r=0|accessdate=December 17, 2014|date=December 17, 2014| work = The New York Times | first1 = David E. | last1 = Sanger | first2 = Nicole | last2= Perlroth }}</ref> White House officials treated the situation as a "serious national security matter",<ref>{{Cite web | url =http://news-briefs.ew.com/2014/12/18/white-house-sony-interview-north-korea/ | title =  White House is treating Sony hack as 'serious national security matter' | work = [[Entertainment Weekly]] | date = December 18, 2014 | accessdate = December 18, 2014 | first = Ariana | last = Bacle }}</ref> and the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) formally stated that they had connected the North Korean government to the cyber-attack.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.fbi.gov/news/pressrel/press-releases/update-on-sony-investigation | title = 
FBI — Update on Sony Investigation| date = December 19, 2014 | accessdate = December 22, 2014 | publisher = [[FBI]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2014/12/19/sony-the-interview-hackers-gop/20635449/ | title = FBI confirms North Korea behind Sony hack | first1 = Elizabeth | last1 = Weise | first2 = Kevin | last2= Johnson | work = [[USA Today]] | date = December 19, 2014 | accessdate = December 19, 2014 }}</ref>

On 8 October 2018, [[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]] reported a North Korean hacking group had tried to steal at least $1.1 billion in a series of attacks on global banks from 2014-2018, as uncovered by cybersecurity company [[FireEye]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Onaran|first=Yalman|date=8 October 2018|title=North Korea Hackers Tried to Take $1.1 Billion in Bank Attacks|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-10-08/north-korea-hackers-broke-into-banks-tried-to-take-1-1-billion |publisher=Bloomberg|access-date=9 October 2018}}</ref>

==International responses==
The [[United Nations Security Council]] has passed multiple [[List of United Nations Security Council resolutions concerning North Korea|resolutions against North Korea]] and its weapons program including, [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 825|UNSC Resolution 825]] (May 1993), [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1695|UNSC Resolution 1695]] (July 2006), [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1874|UNSC 1874]] (June 2009), [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 2094|UNSC Resolution 2094]] (March 2013) and most recently,  [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 2371|UNSC Resolution 2371]] (August 2017). Were the international community to fully enforce UNSC 1874, it is estimated that North Korea would lose between $1.5 and $3.7 billion.<ref name="CRS1874"/>{{rp|4}}

Since 1950, the United States has maintained an [[North Korea–United States relations|embargo against North Korea]] for their role in starting the [[Korean War]]. The embargo and related sanctions have been extended to combat North Korea's various illicit activities and continued aggression.

In 2005, under the [[US Patriot Act]] section 311, $25 million of North Korea's cash was frozen at Macau-based [[Banco Delta Asia]], which the US Treasury said North Korea used for illicit activities.<ref name="CRS1874">{{cite web|url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/nuke/R40684.pdf|title=North Korea's Second Nuclear Test: Implications of U.N. Security Council Resolution 1874|author=Mary Beth Nitkin|publisher=Congressional Research Service|date=April 15, 2010|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref>{{rp|13}}

In 2010, US President [[Barack Obama]] signed [[Executive order (United States)|Executive Order]] 13551, which "targets North Korea’s importation and exportation of arms, importation of luxury goods, and other illicit activities, including money laundering, the counterfeiting of goods and currency, bulk cash smuggling, and narcotics trafficking."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/tg1146.aspx|title=Treasury Designates Financial Institution Involved in Facilitating North Korea's Illicit Activities|publisher=U.S. Department of the Treasury|date=April 19, 2011|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref>

