A '''social bot''' (also: '''''socialbot''''' or '''''socbot''''') is a particular type of [[chatbot]] that is employed in [[social media]] networks to automatically generate messages (e.g. [[Twitter|tweets]]) or in general [[advocate]] certain ideas, support [[Advertising campaign|campaign]]s, and [[public relation]]s either by acting as a "[[Ghost followers|follower]]" or even as a fake account that gathers followers itself. In this respect, social bots can be said to have passed the [[Turing test]].<ref name="techtarget"/> <ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/20/fashion/social-media-bots-offer-phony-friends-and-real-profit.html</ref> Social bots appear to have played a significant role in the [[United States presidential election, 2016]]<ref>Bessi, A & Ferrara, E. (2016) Social Bots Distort the 2016 US Presidential election online discussion. First Monday 21(11), 2016</ref><ref>{{cite arXiv |last=Shao |first=Chengcheng |author2=Giovanni Luca Ciampaglia |author3=Onur Varol |author4=Kaicheng Yang |author5=Alessandro Flammini |author6=Filippo Menczer |eprint=1707.07592 |title=The spread of low-credibility content by social bots |year=2018 }}</ref> and their history appears to go back at least to the [[United States midterm elections, 2010]].<ref name="astroturf">{{cite conference|last=Ratkiewicz |first=Jacob|author2=Michael Conover |author3=Mark Meiss |author4=Bruno Gonçalves |author5=Alessandro Flammini |author6=Filippo Menczer |title=Detecting and Tracking Political Abuse in Social Media |book-title=Proc. 5th International AAAI Conf. on Web and Social Media (ICWSM) |year=2011 |url= http://www.aaai.org/ocs/index.php/ICWSM/ICWSM11/paper/view/2850}}</ref> It is estimated that 9-15% of active Twitter accounts may be social bots<ref name="bot_estimation" /> and that 15% of the total Twitter population active in the US Presidential election discussion were bots. At least 400,000 thousand bots were responsible for about 3.8 million tweets, roughly 19% of the total volume.<ref>Bessi, A & Ferrara, E. (2016) Social Bots Distort the 2016 US Presidential election online discussion. First Monday 21(11), 2016</ref> All these claims are disputed.{{cn|date=July 2018}}
[[Twitterbot]]s are already well-known examples, but corresponding [[autonomous agent]]s on [[Facebook]] and elsewhere have also been observed. Nowadays, social bots can generate convincing [[internet persona]]s that are well capable of influencing real people,<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[First Monday (journal)|First Monday]]|title=Social bots distort the 2016 U.S. Presidential election online discussion |author=Alessandro Bessi and Emilio Ferrara|date=2016-11-07|url=http://firstmonday.org/ojs/index.php/fm/article/view/7090/5653}}</ref><ref name="techtarget">{{cite web|url=http://whatis.techtarget.com/definition/socialbot|publisher=whatis.techtarget.com|title=What is socialbot? - Definition from WhatIs.com|accessdate=2016-12-16}}</ref><ref name="RiseOfSocialBots" /> although they are not always reliable.<ref>[https://au.news.yahoo.com/a/36619546/china-kills-ai-chatbots-after-they-start-criticising-communism/#page1 China kills AI chatbots after they start praising US, criticising communists] Yahoo! News August 5, 2017</ref>
Social bots, besides being able to produce messages autonomously, also share many traits with [[spambot]]s with respect to their tendency to infiltrate large user groups.<ref>{{cite arXiv |last=Ferrara |first=Emilio |eprint=1708.08134 |title=Measuring social spam and the effect of bots on information diffusion in social media |year=2017 }}</ref>
Using social bots is against the terms of service of many platforms, especially Twitter <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://help.twitter.com/en/rules-and-policies/twitter-automation|title=Automation rules|language=en|access-date=2018-11-15}}</ref> and Instagram <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/about/legal/terms/before-january-19-2013/|title=Terms of Use • Instagram|website=www.instagram.com|language=en|access-date=2018-11-15}}</ref>. However many users, especially businesses still automate their Instagram activity in order to gain real followers rather than buying fake ones. This is commonly done through third-party social automation companies.
Unless strict regulations on their use are passed, socialbots are expected to play a major role in future shaping of [[public opinion]] by autonomously acting as incessant and never-tiring [[influencer marketing|influencers]].<ref>{{cite web|title=How robots could shape Germany's political future|publisher=The Local|date=21 November 2016|url=http://www.thelocal.de/20161121/social-bots-robots-germany-elections-future|quote="Social Bots" were the sinister cyber friend in the US elections who didn't actually exist. Could they also shape how Germans vote next year? }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/the-rise-of-political-bots-on-social-media/a-19450562|title=The rise of political bots on social media |date= August 6, 2016|publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]]}}</ref><ref name=bbc>{{cite web|publisher=BBC|title=How online 'chatbots' are already tricking you|quote=Intelligent machines that can pass for humans have long been dreamed of, but as Chris Baraniuk argues, they’re already among us.|url=http://www.bbc.com/future/story/20140609-how-online-bots-are-tricking-you|date=2014-06-09}}</ref>
==Uses== Lutz Finger identifies 5 immediate uses for social bots:<ref>{{cite web|date=Feb 17, 2015|title=Do Evil - The Business Of Social Media Bots|author=Lutz Finger|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/lutzfinger/2015/02/17/do-evil-the-business-of-social-media-bots/#5ffe3e801104|publisher=forbes.com}}</ref> *foster [[Notability|fame]]: having an arbitrary number of (unrevealed) bots as (fake) followers can help simulate real success *[[spamming]]: having advertising bots in online chats is similar to email spam, but a lot more direct *[[mischief]]: e.g. signing up an opponent with a lot of fake identities and spam the account or help others discover it to discreditize the opponent *[[bias]] [[public opinion]]: influence [[Fad|trends]] by countless messages of similar content with different phrasings *limit [[free speech]]: important messages can be pushed out of sight by a deluge of automated bot messages The effects of all points can be likened to and support methods of traditional [[psychological warfare]].
==Detection== The first generation of bots could sometimes be distinguished from real users by their often [[superhuman]] capacities to post messages around the clock (and at massive rates). Later developments have succeeded in imprinting more "human" activity and [[behavioural pattern]]s in the agent.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Romanov|first=Aleksei|author2=Alexander Semenov|author3=Oleksiy Mazhelis|author4=Jari Veijalainen|title=Detection of Fake Profiles in Social Media - Literature Review |journal=Proceedings of the 13th International Conference on Web Information Systems and Technologies|date=2017|url=http://www.scitepress.org/DigitalLibrary/Link.aspx?doi=10.5220/0006362103630369}}</ref> To unambiguously detect social bots as what they are, a variety of criteria must be applied together using [[pattern detection]] techniques, some of which are:<ref name="RiseOfSocialBots">{{cite journal |last1=Ferrara |first1=Emilio |last2=Varol |first2=Onur |last3=Davis |first3=Clayton |last4=Menczer |first4=Filippo |last5=Flammini |first5=Alessandro |year=2016 |title=The Rise of Social Bots |journal=Communications of the ACM |volume=59 |issue=7 |pages=96–104 |doi=10.1145/2818717 |url=http://cacm.acm.org/magazines/2016/7/204021-the-rise-of-social-bots/fulltext|arxiv=1407.5225 }}</ref> *[[cartoon]] figures as user pictures *sometimes also random real user pictures are captured ([[identity fraud]]) *reposting rate *temporal patterns *sentiment expression *followers-to-friends ratio<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socialmediaexaminer.com/find-and-remove-fake-followers-from-twitter-and-instagram/|title=How to Find and Remove Fake Followers from Twitter and Instagram : Social Media Examiner|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.twitteraudit.com/|title=TwitterAudit|publisher=}}</ref> *length of [[user name]]s *variability in (re)posted messages Botometer<ref>{{cite web|url=http://botometer.org/|title=Botometer}}</ref> (formerly BotOrNot) is a public Web service that checks the activity of a Twitter account and gives it a score based on how likely the account is to be a bot. The system leverages over a thousand features.<ref>{{cite conference|last=Davis|first=Clayton A.|author2=Onur Varol|author3=Emilio Ferrara|author4=Alessandro Flammini|author5=Filippo Menczer|title= BotOrNot: A System to Evaluate Social Bots|book-title=Proc. WWW Developers Day Workshop|year=2016|doi=10.1145/2872518.2889302}}</ref><ref name="bot_estimation">{{cite conference|last=Varol|first=Onur|author2=Emilio Ferrara|author3=Clayton A. Davis|author4=Filippo Menczer|author5=Alessandro Flammini|title=Online Human-Bot Interactions: Detection, Estimation, and Characterization |book-title=Proc. International AAAI Conf. on Web and Social Media (ICWSM)|year=2017|url=https://aaai.org/ocs/index.php/ICWSM/ICWSM17/paper/view/15587}}</ref> An active method that worked well in detecting early spam bots was to set up [[honeypot (computing)|honeypot]] accounts where obvious nonsensical content was posted and then dumbly reposted (retweeted) by bots.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=technologyreview.com|title=How to Spot a Social Bot on Twitter|quote=Social bots are sending a significant amount of information through the Twittersphere. Now there’s a tool to help identify them|date=2014-07-28 |url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/529461/how-to-spot-a-social-bot-on-twitter/}}</ref> Another method of detection is analysis of speed of change of the social network metrics: in particular, number of friends or followers for social bot grows very quickly, and clustering stays very low. That is explained by usage of "friend farm" services to collect large number of friends in a short period of time.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Romanov|first=Aleksei|author2=Alexander Semenov|author3=Jari Veijalainen|title=Revealing Fake Profiles in Social Networks by Longitudinal Data Analysis |journal=Proceedings of the 13th International Conference on Web Information Systems and Technologies|date=2017|url=http://www.scitepress.org/DigitalLibrary/Link.aspx?doi=10.5220%2f0006243900510058}}</ref>
